INSERT INTO `answer` VALUES ('Q_001','M0','Philadelphia, there is help out there. For your daughter\'s sake, start somewhere. Feelings are only that; your worst fears about who you are are only based on a few moments that haven\'t gone well. Depression is so treatable, but you have to seek treatment from a professional.Here\'s a quick exercise for you to do that can show you how therapy might work... fear is telling you the worst possible story of your life, right? So... if there was an opposite story...the very best story that someone could tell about you and your life...what would that be? Who would be telling it? Someone who loves you? Someone who was around you when you were that outgoing person? Someone who\'s been watching your life from the start? God? Write that best story. I dare you to give it as much credibility as the worst one.Â Therapy is often about helping people reject their \"worst stories\". I invite you to start exploring with a qualified therapist whatever barriers stand between you and your best life. I hope you reach out soon. :)'),('Q_001','M2',' Are you depressed?Ã‚Â  Is this a new issue?I understand youÃ¢â‚¬â„¢re feeling down but you want to be happy and outgoing again. Ã‚Â I suggest that you contact your primary care physician because these are symptoms of depression. Ã‚Â I want to point out thatÃ‚Â depression is treatable and a lot of people have overcome depression.Good luck!'),('Q_001','M3',' You mentioned you want to be happy and outgoing again. Do you remember when you last felt happy and outgoing? How did that feel? What activities did you do that made you feel that way?What did your daughter enjoy doing with you when you were feeling happy and outgoing? It\'s possible that your daughter also noticed that you were more outgoing and happy. If she was happy to see you more outgoing and happy, that could motivate you to make an effort to put yourself in situations where you feel more positive.'),('Q_001','M4','I\'m sorry to hear about your situation. I\'m glad you wrote. I wonder if you\'ve tried to talk with your husband about your feelings. If you haven\'t, maybe you can start there. I wonder if you can talk about your feelings with him. I wonder if you'),('Q_001','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are feeling this way. It sounds like you are experiencing a lot of emotions and thoughts that are overwhelming. I would encourage you to seek out a therapist who can help you work through these feelings and thoughts. A therapist can help you identify the root causes of your feelings and thoughts and work with you to develop coping strategies to manage them. I hope you find the help you need.'),('Q_002','M0','Are there any times or moments in which you feel other than \"empty\"? Â Start with knowing the context of when you feel something other than empty.If there is no recent example, then in your mind, go back in time to think of when you felt something other than empty. Â Recall what you liked about this time, whether you were by yourself or with others, what type of activity you were involved at the time of non-emptiness.How did you come to your conclusion that your life purpose is to reproduce and die? Â If this is what your parents, siblings and extended family believe, it is possible that you have a broader view of yourself and haven\'t yet uncovered a way of defining your own philosophy of living.Give yourself the time to browse around online, or in person social meet ups, on your interests. Â It is possible you will discover entire new areas of life and ways of considering life, that are brand new to you and which connect to your true self.This is one way of respecting your individuality, which of itself, may decrease your sense of emptiness.'),('Q_002','M2',' Thank you for sharing your thoughts and feelings about the meaning of life. It\'s understandable why you would feel empty and uncertain about your life\'s purpose if you believe that the only purpose is to reproduce and die. It might be helpful for you to consider other perspectives on the meaning of life. Some people find meaning in connecting with others, giving back to the community, or helping others. Others find meaning in personal growth and self-discovery. There are many different ways to find meaning and purpose in life, and it\'s important to find what resonates with you.'),('Q_002','M3',' It may be helpful to find resources and information that can help you with your feelings of emptiness.Ã‚Â  It may also be beneficial to talk to a therapist to get a better understanding of why you\'re feeling this way and can help you change it.'),('Q_002','M4','I\'m sorry to hear that you feel empty. I wonder if you are feeling empty because you are not living up to your potential. I would recommend that you find a purpose in your life. What is something that you are passionate about?  What is something that you have always wanted to do?  If you can find something that you are passionate about and you can make it happen, you will feel fulfilled. I hope this helps. Best of luck. ~Mark (www. MarkMorrisLCSW. com and www. LivingYes. org)\n\nFrom your question, I am wondering if you are feeling empty because you are not living up to your potential. I would recommend that you find something that you are passionate about and make it happen. org)\n\nFrom your question, I am wondering if you are not living up to your potential. org)\n\nFrom your question, I am wondering if you are not living up'),('Q_002','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are feeling empty. I wonder if you have ever considered that you may be experiencing a sense of meaninglessness?  This is a common experience for many people. It is not uncommon for people to feel empty, even when they have a lot going on in their lives. It is possible that you are experiencing a sense of meaninglessness. This can happen when we feel disconnected from our values, our purpose, or our sense of self. It can also happen when we feel like we are not making a difference in the world. If you are experiencing a sense of meaninglessness, it may be helpful to explore what is important to you and what gives your life meaning. You may also want to consider talking to a therapist who can help you explore these issues and develop a plan for finding more meaning in your life.'),('Q_003','M0','Oh dear.From what you write, your husband doesn\'t have any interest to know about you and your sad feelings.Stay clear in understanding that you already did your part by asking him to listen and care about the way you feel.In this example, he told you he doesn\'t care.Its up to him to open his mind and heart to you.Depending on how motivated to continue asking him to hear you, try until you feel satisfied that you\'ve given him enough chances to know who you are. Â  At a certain number of tries at this, you\'ll either have success or not.Just don\'t try forever because doing so will increase your depressed feelings.'),('Q_003','M2',' First of all, I want to say how sorry I am that your husband isn\'t taking seriously the pain you are experiencing. You deserve to be heard and to have your feelings respected. You can start by telling him that the way he dismissed you really hurt your feelings. Use an \"I\" statement, such as, \"When you ignored me, I felt like I wasn\'t being heard.\" Try to avoid blaming your husband or using \"you\" statements, as that can lead to defensiveness. If he still is not getting it, see if your doctor or a local therapist might provide some direction in getting through to him. You could also suggest attending a couples counseling session. Good luck!'),('Q_003','M3',' It sounds like your husband may be struggling to understand or validate your experience. He may be minimizing or dismissing your emotions because he doesn\'t know what to do or how to help. I recommend that you have a nonjudgmental conversation with your husband about how you\'re feeling. Be specific about what you\'re experiencing and how it\'s affecting your life. Let him know that you\'re not just \"sad or depressed,\" but that you are concerned about your mental health and that you want his support. You could also suggest that you both go to a couples therapist to learn how to communicate with each other more effectively and to work through the issues that are affecting your marriage.'),('Q_003','M4','I\'m sorry to hear that you are feeling ignored. I would ask you to think about what your husband\'s reasons are for ignoring you. Is he unaware of your feelings?  Is he unaware of your feelings?  Is he unaware of your feelings?  If you can answer these questions, you can then figure out how to communicate with him. If you are aware of his reasons, you can then figure out how to communicate with him. If you are not aware of his reasons, you can ask him.'),('Q_003','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that your husband is not taking your depression seriously. It is important to have a partner who is supportive and understanding of your mental health. If your husband is not willing to listen to you, it may be helpful to seek out a therapist who can provide you with the support and validation you need. A therapist can also help you to communicate your needs to your husband in a way that is effective and respectful. Remember, your mental health is important and you deserve to be heard and supported by your partner. Best of luck to you!'),('Q_004','M0','Hello,While one can be sad from time to time, feeling sad \"all the time\" could be a sign of depression. If you feel sad on most days, it is worthwhile speaking to a psychologist to determine whether you suffer clinical depression. Feeling sadness is a normal response to loss, whether you lose a family, friend, job, or something you deem important in your life. However, feeling sadness all the time is a signal that you are not happy about something in your life. If it is related to your family and often relationship with family members could affect our self-esteem and self-worth, then perhaps it is worthwhile exploring what you find unhappy about your relationship with your family. Is it that you do not feel heard, supported or loved? Is it that you feel disrespected, disregarded or feel unimportant? These are just a few examples of common issues that people report that contribute to their depression. To help you to uncover your reasons for your sadness or depression and to cope with them in a healthier and more constructive way, it may be helpful to contact a therapist who could support you with this process. You do not have to deal with it alone. Dr. Virginia Chow, Montreal Psychologist. For more information about depression, please consult my website at www.PsychologyResource.ca'),('Q_004','M2',' Feeling sad all the time, and not liking the people in your family, can be very difficult. Ã‚Â It seems that you feel like your family is trying to control you and not allowing you to grow. Ã‚Â This can be very frustrating and isolating. Ã‚Â I encourage you to talk to your family about how you feel. Ã‚Â Express your frustrations and let them know you are feeling controlled. Ã‚Â Try to come up with some solutions together that will allow you to have more control over your own life.'),('Q_004','M3',' Sorry to hear that you are going through this. It is important to process some of these feelings that you are having. There are some good resources that can help you cope. The first would be to find a therapist that can help you understand and work through these feelings. The second one would be to read some books on the subject. There are some great books out there that can help you gain some clarity. Here are a few books that I would recommend:\n1. The Power of Now by Eckhart Tolle\n2. The Four Agreements by Don Miguel Ruiz\n3. Man\'s Search For Meaning by Viktor Frankl\n4. The Four Loves by C.S. Lewis\n5. The Five Love Languages by Gary Chapman'),('Q_004','M4','nan - I\'m sorry to hear this. I\'m glad you\'re aware of your feelings. I\'m curious if you\'ve tried to talk to your family about this?  I wonder if they know how you feel?  If not, maybe you can start there. I wonder if you can talk to them about how you feel and if they\'re willing to listen. If they are, maybe you can talk about what you need from them. Maybe they can help you find a therapist or something like that. I wonder if you can find a therapist for yourself. I wonder if'),('Q_004','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are feeling sad and that you feel like your family is trying to control you. It sounds like you are feeling very alone and that you are not getting the support you need. I would encourage you to talk to a therapist about your feelings and to get some support. A therapist can help you to understand your feelings and to develop coping skills to deal with them. They can also help you to develop better communication skills with your family so that you can express your needs and have your needs met. I wish you the best of luck!'),('Q_005','M0','Sometimes the way to feel happy is to address all the questions you just described.Teenage years are the first time any of us starts to feel and recognize our uniqueness. Â The fact that you recognize your great range of feelings, as uncomfortable as they may sometimes be, is healthy.Also healthy is that you are asking for opinions of therapists who would be familiar with when a range of feelings shows an out of the ordinary problem.One path to take is to reflect on the topics you wrote here and especially to ask yourself your reasons for how the problem started and what it would take for it to resolve.Do you have trust issues because someone broke your trust?Â You\'re entitled to a repair of your trust by the other person. Â  Even if the person never offers this to you, to know you deserve to be restored to whole, may help you feel more secure.The same is true with the other topics, abandonment and relationships generally.The more you continue to value your unique understanding, expectations, and st