you are aware of the impact of your behavior on the world. I wonder if you are aware of the impact of your behavior on the universe. I wonder if you are aware of the impact of your behavior on the cosmos. I wonder'),('Q_010','M5','I would suggest that you and your fiancée have a conversation about what is going on. If you are not comfortable having this conversation, then you may want to consider seeing a therapist. A therapist can help you and your fiancée to understand each other\'s needs and to work through any issues that may be causing the fights. If you are not comfortable with seeing a therapist, then you may want to consider talking to a trusted friend or family member about what is going on. They may be able to offer you some advice or support.'),('Q_011','M0','Try doing something physical. If you haven\'t exercised before, it is a good idea to get your doctor\'s approval first, but this can be helpful.The more you can find out about when you want to cut, the easier it will be to figure out what else you can do. If you are feeling sad or angry or nervous, look at what is leading up to those feelings and talk to someone about that.You said you are alone. I would see if you can find someone that you can trust to talk with about what you are going through. This could be a parent, a friend, someone at school, a coworker, or any number of other people.'),('Q_011','M2',' I would want to know how you feel sad enough to want to hurt yourself.I would encourage you to seek help if you are having negative feelings about yourself -- a therapist can help you to develop coping mechanisms that help you to manage negative feelings.'),('Q_011','M3',' Cutting yourself is not something you should be doing.Ã‚Â  It\'s a sign of being extremely stressed and hurting emotionally.Ã‚Â  I\'m so sorry you are sad and alone.Ã‚Â  I encourage you to go to a trusted adult and talk to them about what\'s wrong.Ã‚Â  If you\'re not comfortable talking to someone you know, there are a number of free and confidential resources to which I can refer you.Ã‚Â  Cutting yourself is not the answer.Ã‚Â  There are other healthier ways to deal with stress and the difficulties in life that we all face.Ã‚Â  I want you to be safe and well.Ã‚Â  Please let me know if I can help.'),('Q_011','M4','I\'m sorry to hear about this. I would recommend finding a therapist who can help you work through this. It\'s not uncommon for people to self harm when they are feeling sad. It\'s important to find a therapist who can help you find other ways to cope. I hope you find someone to help you. Best of luck. You are not alone. There are people out there who can help you. You just have to find the right therapist'),('Q_011','M5','I\'m so sorry to hear that you are feeling this way. I\'m glad you are reaching out for help. I would encourage you to reach out to a local crisis line or suicide prevention hotline. You can also reach out to a local mental health professional. They can help you to find a therapist who can help you to work through these feelings. I hope you find the help you need. You are not alone. There are people who care about you and want to help you. You are loved. You are not'),('Q_012','M0','Hello, and thank you for your question. This is a very serious time. I don\'t mean to frighten you, but you are right to be concerned. The time right after people leave the hospital after receiving psychiatric services is a time of high risk for suicide. It is very important, after hospitalization,Â to getÂ follow-up care with a professional as soon as possible. If your husband has an established therapist, this is the time to call. It is also a good time to alert your support system of friends, family, clergy or others to let them know he is still struggling. This is good support for him AND you.It is important to think about means and opportunity to make another attempt. Means really do matter.Â  So, if you have a firearm in the home, it is really important to remove it. You can\'t remove all things that a person may hurt themselves with, but some things are more lethal than others. Firearms are very lethal. I am not sure what means he used last time, but try to reduce the opportunity for him to access it again. This is where your support system can help out. People can take turns hanging out with him until you are sure the crisis is over.If you believe that an attempt is going to occur, talk to your husband about going back to the hospital. If he refuses, you will want to find out what your options are to have him go even if he doesn\'t want to. I know the thought of that really hurts, but it can save his life. Calling 9-1-1 is alwaysÂ aÂ good option if you are not sure. Usually a suicide crisis, meaning they want to harm themselves right now, lasts a few minutes, hours or days. Sometimes when you get them through the crisis stage, they no longer want to commit suicide. But, as you are indicating, that feeling of wanting to commit suicide can come back again. So, it is always good to have a plan. If you want more information, call the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline. They will always answer: 1-800-273-8255. They can help you create a specific safety plan. I do hope things work out alright. Be well. Robin J. Landwehr, DBH, LPCC, NCC'),('Q_012','M2',' Thanks for reaching out. It\'s very common for a person to experience all kinds of emotions after they\'ve experienced a suicidal crisis. One of the reasons for this is that he may now feel a sense of guilt or shame around his previous thoughts of suicide. It may take a bit of time for him to come around emotionally from some of these difficult emotions. It is important that he continue to get the support that he needs. For example, he may benefit from seeing a therapist or counselor if he isn\'t already working with someone. I hope this helps.'),('Q_012','M3',' Depression is often a result of chemical imbalances in the brain. If your husband stopped taking his medication for depression, then he is likely experiencing the effects of withdrawing from his medication. Talk with your husband about going back on his medication so that his depression can be effectively treated.'),('Q_012','M4','nan - I\'m so sorry to hear this. I\'m glad you\'re here to support him. I\'m not sure if you\'re in the same place as he is, but I\'m wondering if you\'ve seen him since he got home. I\'m wondering if you\'ve seen him since he got home. I\'m wondering'),('Q_012','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that your husband is struggling with depression. It can be very difficult to know how to help someone who is depressed. I would encourage you to talk with your husband about how he is feeling. It may be helpful to ask him what he thinks is causing his depression. It may also be helpful to ask him what he thinks would help him feel better. If he is open to talking about it, you may also want to encourage him to talk with his doctor about his depression. A doctor can help him find the right treatment for him. I hope this helps!'),('Q_013','M0','The fact that you\'re reaching out says that there is something in you that wants this to be different, and that drive might be something worth tapping into. \"Why do I keep trying?\" is a question that might give you some insight into what it is in you that keeps you going.Â A lot of therapists/counselors are now offering video therapy. As long as you\'re in the same state as a therapist offering this service, you could connect with someone helpful from the comfort of your home, even being in your small town. I\'d recommend looking into this option, because you\'re asking a lot of really deep questions and might benefit from having those conversations with someone who can help you find your own answers.'),('Q_013','M2',' You serve a very distinct and invaluable purpose in this life. I say this because you are experiencing the loneliness and depression of an unfulfilled purpose, and you are seeking answers. Many others would not bother to take 