ou learn new coping skills and strategies to help you manage your depression and anxiety. It can also be a great way to explore the root causes of your depression and anxiety and work through any underlying issues that may be contributing to your symptoms. If you are interested in finding a counselor in your area, you can search online or ask your primary care physician for a referral. Good luck!'),('Q_021','M0','Hi Boise, I\'m sorry that you\'ve lost this love. The fact that you were planning marriage and a future tells me that you meant something very special to each other at that time. It\'s different now...you\'re not together anymore, but you can\'t accept this, right? Good for you for identifying that this situation is damaging your life. You\'ve been grieving for longer than you were together. Oh, but really you\'ve not been grieving...you\'re stuck still loving her instead of moving forward. Unrequited love is a recipe for eternal heartache. Let\'s look at some possible blocks to moving forward.It could be that there\'s something unfinished for you. Maybe you felt hurt and you didn\'t have the chance to say so, or you felt you hurt her and you didn\'t have the chance to make it right. Maybe there\'s a burning question you need to ask or something else you need to say. Maybe you want to tell her you\'ve never stopped loving her, and see if she feels the same way. If this is the case, you have two choices, right? You can reach out and say what you need to say, or you can stop ruminating on that question and let it go. If you reach out, there\'s no guarantee it will go well or that she\'ll even respond. Maybe write her a letter and don\'t send it (or send it...it might be worth the risk). Use the next paragraph to help you decide.Â Do you know how she feels? How did it end? Did she end it? Was it ended just because of the distance, or are there more differences between you that didn\'t work? Sometimes people are so in love that they can\'t clearly see that the other person isn\'t in love with them anymore. Use the information you have about what she wants for her life...can you honour what she says she needs? If she\'s asked for distance, you would do well to honour that.A key to moving forward: look at your thoughts and where they\'re getting stuck. Write it down. What bad thing can happen if you let it go? Or \"If I move forward, that will mean...\" Â Keep going...what would be the worst part of that? Â This kind of exploring can help you identify your stuck place.It is possible that you\'ve turned this ending into some kind of negative meaning about you or your future. As in \"If this person doesn\'t love me, then I\'m unlovable\", or \"No one will ever love me as much as she did\". So your need to cling to her in your heart is your way of rejecting that negative message about yourself or the future. Can you find another way to reject that message? Try saying these things to yourself:I know she loved me. There is evidence of that.I was a good partner. There is evidence of that.It\'s part of life to fall in love and then have to move forward...I can do this and learn from it.Many people like me...that\'s how I know I\'m lovable.It\'s normal to feel sad. I\'m grieving a lost love.I want to move forward and not stare in the rearview mirror.I know more love awaits me if I can get fear out of the way.If this person loved me, others can too, (but not if I\'m clinging to some old memory)These are the kinds of things a therapist would explore with you. I wish you well!'),('Q_021','M2',' I\'m sorry to hear about that. It sounds like you have a lot of unanswered questions. Are you still in contact with your ex? Were you able to get closure on the break up? Are you seeing a therapist? It may be helpful to talk with a therapist about the breakup and process your feelings. You also may want to consider writing a letter to your ex. This doesn\'t have to be sent, and can be an opportunity for you to get some of your feelings out in the open.'),('Q_021','M3',' I understand that you are trying to move on from your past relationship; however, you are not able to because you still harbor feelings for your ex-partner. It is normal to feel like you are stuck when it comes to relationships, especially if you were seriously involved with someone for an extended period. However, if you are unable to move forward from your past relationship because you still have feelings for your ex, then it may be helpful to seek professional counseling to help you properly process and move on from your past relationship.Ã‚Â '),('Q_021','M4','I\'m sorry to hear about your breakup. I\'m glad you are aware of your feelings. Depression is a common reaction to a breakup. I wonder if you are able to talk with your ex about your feelings. I wonder if you'),('Q_021','M5','I\'m sorry to hear about your depression. It sounds like you are still in love with your ex-girlfriend. It is possible that you are experiencing what is called \"unrequited love\". This is when you are in love with someone who does not love you back. It is very painful to be in this situation. It is possible that you are experiencing depression because you are not getting the love and affection you need from your ex-girlfriend. It is also possible that you are experiencing depression because you are not getting the love and affection you need from someone else. If you are not getting the love and affection you need from someone else, it may be time to find someone who can give you what you need. If you are not getting the love and affection you need from your ex-girlfriend, it may be time to move on and find someone who can give you what you need. I hope this helps.'),('Q_022','M0','You\'re probably not going to like my answer.Your question says a lot about what YOU want rather than what she wants or what may be best for her. Sometimes, what\'s best for a person is the hardest thing to do, and may be completely opposite of what YOU want.Addictions don\'t happen in a vacuum. If you\'ve had any experience with addicts at all, then I\'m sure you\'ve heard the term \"enabler\". A lot of the times, when people think they\'re \"helping\", they\'re actually enabling the addict to continue their self-destructive behavior. Tough love and clear boundaries are needed in a lot of situations, but especially with addictions. Family and friends are often the biggest contributing factor to someone choosing to use/drink, continuing to do so, or relapsing back into it.You said she recently quit. You said she is depressed. She wants to move. When a person receives counseling for addictions, they are encouraged to make changes like this. They need to break the habit, and this means removing people from their lives at times. It means moving to new locations. Anything that may trigger a relapse needs to be identified and removed. Not only that, but the addict needs to do a lot of personal reflection to figure out WHY they use/drink in the first place, and not only break the physical addiction to it, but deal with whatever is the root cause that led them to use in the first place. She may need some time alone to figure out who she is as a person, time to make some decisions for herself and do what she needs to do to be healthy.Don\'t pressure her to stay. Let her have the freedom to do what she needs to do. If she stays, the decision needs to be hers and hers alone. It doesn\'t need to be made under pressure. That will only lead to resentment. Support her, but don\'t try to change her or make her do anything, especially for selfish reasons. Let her go. It sounds like she needs some time to focus on herself right now. It wouldn\'t be a bad idea for you to do the same.'),('Q_022','M2',' I hear that you are worried that your girlfriend will move. I\'m glad that you are reaching out to get some support so that you can feel less worried.Ã‚Â A major life change, such as quitting alcohol, can cause a lot of depression and sadness. In order to help her, you can be there to listen and support her. Let her know that she is not alone and that you are there for her. You can also encourage her to seek professional help so that she can work through her depression. I hope this helps.Ã‚Â If you are worried about her safety, please call the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline at 800-273-8255.'),('Q_022','M3',' Moving can be a very difficult and stressful experience, as many changes will need to be made.Ã‚Â  She may be feeling a bit overwhelmed with the idea of moving, and the thought of it might be making her depressed.Ã‚Â  It is important to talk to your girlfriend about what is causing her depression, and to support her in her decision to quit drinking.Ã‚Â  Quitting drinking can be very difficult and depressing, and she may need some extra support.Encourage her to talk to a therapist or counselor, as they can help her to understand why she is feeling depressed.Ã‚Â  Support her in making healthy choices, such as eating a healthy diet and exercising regularly.Ã‚Â  Let her know that you are there for her, and that she is not alone.Ã‚Â  Be patient with her, and understand that she is going through a very difficult time.'),('Q_022','M4','nan - nan - nan - I\'m not sure if you\'re asking for advice or just to vent. I\'m not sure if you\'re asking for advice or just venting. I\'m not sure'),('Q_022','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that your girlfriend is struggling with depression. It can be very difficult to see someone you care about in pain. It sounds like you want to help her, and that\'s a great thing. I would encourage you to talk to her about what she is going through. It may be helpful to ask her what she needs from you right now. It may also be helpful to ask her what she needs from you in the future. It\'s important to remember that you can\'t make her feel better, but you can be there for her and support her. If she does decide to move, I would encourage you to continue to be there for her and support her in any way you can. It\'s important to remember that she is going through a difficult time, and she needs your support. I hope this helps.'),('Q_023','M0','Not having support from your family for such a significant problem, is a problem itself.How about your friends, are any of them nurturing or treat you kindly when you bring up that you\'ve got this problem?Are any of your friends willing to accommodate the fact that right now you\'ve got panic attacks from driving and being a passenger?Maybe being and feeling accepted while you\'re in this current phase of your life, would help diminish the panic attacks.If no support is coming to you, then a next step would be to evaluate the relationships in your life and to develop standards and expectations of others, especially that they are considerate of your great need at this time.Its possible you are bearing the emotional burden of a lot more people in your life than yourself.If no one wants to show they care about this situation, then release yourself from trying to please and satisfy everyone\'s wish that you be better, while they ignore your need for their support.Be realistic in what you\'re able to give back to people who want to be blind to your emotional need.Thinking this way will at first raise your anxiety level from fear of losing everyone. Â Eventually, you\'ll stabilize within yourself and know that all you\'re asking for is some support for having a tough time.Â Hopefully, the others will be more responsive to you.If they don\'t you still know that you\'re being reasonable for what you\'d like.'),('Q_023','M2',' I\'m so sorry your family is not supportive of you and that you have been struggling with panic attacks for a long time. I\'m glad you are not self-harming and have found the strength to reach out for help. First, I would suggest you see a therapist who specializes in treating anxiety if you are not already seeing one. There are very effective treatments for panic attacks such as CBT (cognitive-behavioral therapy) and relaxation therapy. In addition, a therapist can help you develop coping mechanisms to reduce your anxiety and to handle panic attacks if they do occur.'),('Q_023','M3',' Hi there,I\'m so sorry to hear that you suffer from panic attacks and anxiety. It sounds like you\'re going through a really rough time. It\'s important to know that you\'re not alone and that there are people who can help you. Panic attacks and anxiety can be debilitating. I\'m glad to hear that you\'re aware of this and are looking for ways to cope with them. It\'s important to remember that you\'re not alone. Millions of people suffer from anxiety and panic attacks. There are many things you can do to reduce your anxiety and panic attacks. One important step is to learn more about what triggers them. What situations or activities seem to make you feel particularly anxious or panicky? Once you know what your triggers are, you can start to avoid them or develop strategies to cope with them. Another thing that is really important is to practice relaxation techniques. There are many different types of relaxation techniques, so you can find one that works for you. Some common relaxation techniques include deep breathing, meditation, and yoga. Finally, it\'s important to remember that you\'re not alone. There are many people who suffer from anxiety and panic attacks. There are many resources available to help you find ways to cope with your anxiety and panic attacks. You can talk to your doctor or a therapist, or you can find support groups online. There is hope! You can overcome your anxiety and panic attacks and live a happy and healthy life. I wish you all the best on your journey to recovery from anxiety and panic attacks.'),('Q_023','M4','I\'m so sorry to hear about your situation. I\'m glad you are aware of your anxiety and panic attacks. I would recommend finding a therapist who can help you work through your anxiety and panic attacks. You can also find some great resources online to help you cope with your anxiety and panic attacks. Here is a link to a great resource: https://www. anxiety. org/anxiety-self-help-guide-overcoming-anxiety-symptoms-and-triggers/ I hope this was helpful and I wish you the best of luck!  Be well. Robin Landwehr, DBH, LPC, NCC, CASACounseling@RobinLandwehr. comwww. RobinLandwehr. LivingYes. orgwww. org/blog/2018/03/14/living-yes-living-no-more/www. org/blog/2018/03/14/living-'),('Q_023','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are having such a difficult time. It sounds like you are experiencing a lot of anxiety and panic attacks. It is important to seek help from a mental health professional who can help you to understand the root cause of your anxiety and panic attacks. They can also help you to develop coping strategies to manage your symptoms. It is also important to talk to your family about your struggles and to ask for their support. They may not realize how much you are struggling and may be able to offer you the support you need. I wish you all the best in your journey towards healing and managing your anxiety and panic attacks.'),('Q_024','M0','What kinds of things help you to feel safe?Â  I think it\'s great you\'ve already tried a few things to help yourself sleep, even if they don\'t work.Â  Those methods of coping could be targeting something other than paranoia--which is maybe why you aren\'t finding those things are helpful.Â Â If you are really struggling, sometimes meds can help to calm the brain a bit.Â  If you choose this route, make sure you give your prescribing doctor all the information about your symptoms so your meds can be as accurate as possible for what you\'re dealing with.If you have access, counseling could be beneficial as well.Â  There are more and more counselors becoming available via telehealth because of COVID, so you could even find someone to help you right in the space you feel most paranoid about (given that space is private).Â  Either way, talking some of those fears through could at the very least bring some insight, if not some relief.'),('Q_024','M2',' In your current state, the paranoid feeling is making it difficult for you to sleep. It may help to focus on relaxing your body before going to bed. Many methods are available to help you with this, including listening to relaxing music, visualization techniques, and/or deep breathing. There are several excellent books that provide guidance with relaxing, and you may also want to contact a local therapist who can help you with these techniques.'),('Q_024','M3',' Hi and thank you for contacting me. I\'m so sorry to hear you are struggling with such high levels of paranoia, depression, and anxiety. Paranoia by definition is the tendency to distrust the intentions of others and is a common symptom of underlying anxiety or trauma. As someone who works in the mental health field, I strongly encourage you to reach out for help from a mental health counselor who can assess and diagnose your paranoia, and recommend the best treatment options available. Paranoia can be debilitating and distressing, but is one of the most treatable mental health issues. I hope you will find a therapist who can help you and provide you with the tools to cope with and manage your paranoia. You deserve to feel safe and well. Please reach out and ask for help -- you don\'t have to suffer alone.'),('Q_024','M4','I\'m sorry to hear about your anxiety. I\'m not sure if you are referring to a specific event or just general anxiety. If you are feeling anxious about a specific event, then you can try to understand what is causing it. If you are feeling anxious about everything, then you may want to talk with your primary care physician. They may be able to help you find some answers. I hope you feel better soon. Best of luck!  ~Mark (www. MarkMorrisLCSW. com and www. LivingYes. org)\n\nFrom the blog - Living Yes\n\nYou can reach me at\n\nMarkMorrisLCSW@gmail. com\n\nwww. org\n\nYou can also follow me on,\n\nYou can also follow me 