 written this so that we can talk through this.Name-calling can be really hurtful, especially if it is from someone you know. This does not mean that you have to accept it. It is your choice whether or not you want to continue talking to someone who calls you names.You may have already done this, but if not, I would encourage you to talk to the person or people who are calling you names. Tell them how you feel, and ask them to stop. If they do not stop, then you can choose to stop talking to them.If you are unable to talk to the person or people who are calling you names, then you may want to talk to someone else who you trust, like a family member or a teacher. They can help you come up with ways to deal with this situation.Remember, you do not have to put up with being called names. You have a choice whether or not you want to continue talking to someone who calls you names.'),('Q_025','M4','I am so sorry to hear this. I am glad you are aware of the impact of these names. I wonder if you have told your friends and family about this. I am curious if they know about this. I wonder if they know how much this is bothering you. I wonder if they know how'),('Q_025','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are being called names. It sounds like you are feeling overwhelmed and that you are ready to move on. I would encourage you to find a therapist who can help you process your feelings and develop coping skills. You deserve to be treated with respect and kindness. I wish you the best of luck!'),('Q_026','M0','First of all, if youâ€™re sick and in pain, have you seen your doctor? If you have a chronic illness and pain, this can often lead to depression and is very common. Youâ€™ve taken the first step to dealing with it. You can talk to your doctor, even if your depression isnâ€™t related to your health. He or she can either look at prescribing you an antidepressant or can refer you to a psychologist or psychiatrist.If thatâ€™s not really an option for you, there areÂ also helplines (local or national) or support groups where people dealing withÂ similar issuesÂ can talk to each other. If you can\'t find any in your area (newspapers usually publish this information), there areÂ online support groups as well.'),('Q_026','M2',' It sounds like you are experiencing tremendous emotional and physical pain. I am so sorry that you are experiencing such an extremely difficult time. Please contact The Samaritans, a 24/7 mental health crisis hotline for anyone who is feeling suicidal. You can contact them by calling 116 123 or emailing jo@samaritans.org. They are there to help, and you are not alone.'),('Q_026','M3',' I\'m so sorry to hear that you are experiencing depression. It can be a very difficult and isolating experience. It is important to know that you are not alone, and that there are people who can help. You may have family or friends who can offer support, or you may choose to speak with a therapist, who can provide you with guidance and support as you work through your depression. You can also find a variety of resources available online, including support groups, articles, and blogs about depression. If you are feeling overwhelmed or suicidal, please know that there are resources available to help you, including crisis hotlines and suicide prevention websites. I hope this information is helpful to you, and that you will be able to find the support you need to feel better.'),('Q_026','M4','I\'m sorry to hear about your pain. I would recommend talking to your primary care physician. They can help you find a therapist. I would also recommend calling 211. They can help you find resources in your area. I hope you feel better soon. Best of luck. ~Mark (www. MarkMorrisLCSW. com and www. LivingYes. org)\n\nMark Morris LCSW'),('Q_026','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are feeling depressed. Depression is a very common condition and there are many ways to get help. You can start by talking to your primary care doctor. They can help you find a therapist in your area. You can also call the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline at 1-800-273-8255. They are available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. They can help you find a therapist in your area and provide you with other resources. I hope you find the help you need. Take care.'),('Q_027','M0','Give yourself a little more credit for self-observation!You wrote about treating people horribly and not realizing it. Â Only if you truly didn\'t realize what you were doing, then you wouldn\'t be able to write about it.A little self-examination goes a long way.You have some basic clues about yourself, such as pushing people away whom you love.Start with reflecting on the reasons for your behavior, especially any fears about a negative result from opening your heart to another person.The weird feeling you have is also an area to self-reflect and theorize about. Â From what you write, you have a solid awareness of your feelings. Â This is the place to start understanding more about your hesitation in relationship with others. Â This type of work can be done alone or with a therapist.'),('Q_027','M2',' This sounds like a difficult situation you are navigating. It sounds like you need to process what\'s going on with you. Are you able to speak to a therapist or counselor? You might consider reading a book on emotional intelligence or interpersonal skills to help you understand more about yourself and your interactions.'),('Q_027','M3',' Hello, I am sorry you are having such a difficult time.Ã‚Â Ã‚Â It sounds like you are going through a great deal of emotional pain. Ã‚Â You may also be experiencing depression. Ã‚Â The feeling that you have a \"weird feeling deep down inside\" and that you are \"collapsing\" may indicate this. Ã‚Â I would encourage you to talk with a mental health professional such as a psychotherapist or counselor to get some support in figuring out what is happening to you and how you can start to feel better.'),('Q_027','M4','I\'m sorry to hear about your situation. I\'m not sure if you are in a relationship or not, but I would recommend finding someone to talk to. It\'s important to have someone to talk to about your feelings. I would also recommend finding a therapist to help you work through your feelings. It\'s important to get to the root of what\'s causing you to feel this way. Once you get to the root of the issue, you can start to work through it. I hope this was helpful and I wish you the best of luck. Take care. Mirella~Image and Likeness Counseling www. MirellaImageandLikeness. comwww. Facebook. com/MirellaImageandLikenesswww. Twitter. Pinterest. com/MirellaImageandLikeness/www. Instagram. Flickr. com/photographer/10727617/www. com/photographer/107276'),('Q_027','M5','It sounds like you are feeling overwhelmed and stressed. It is important to take care of yourself and to seek support. You can start by talking to a trusted friend or family member. You can also consider seeing a therapist who can help you work through your feelings and develop coping strategies. Remember, you are not alone and there is help available. Take care.'),('Q_028','M0','It\'s hard to answer this without knowing more specifically the anxiety and depression symptoms you are experiencing - but typically treatment for anxiety and depression is multi-faceted. Going to therapy, working with your primary care doctor to check for (and treat) any physical factors, learning healthy coping strategies for your anxiety and depression, increasing your social support, moving your body in ways that feel good, spending time doing something that\'s meaningful to you - all of these can be helpful for treating anxiety and depression!'),('Q_028','M2',' It sounds like you\'ve been experiencing a lot of stress lately, which can affect your mood and make you feel sad and depressed. It\'s important to know that you\'re not alone in this. Many people experience stress and anxiety, and there are many things you can do to feel better.Ã‚Â One thing that can help is to talk to someone about what\'s going on. If you\'re comfortable talking to a friend or family member, that can be a great place to start. You can also find mental health counselors in the UK who offer free or low-cost therapy.Ã‚Â Another thing that can be helpful is to take care of your physical health. Exercise can help boost your mood and energy levels. Eating a healthy diet and getting enough sleep can also make a big difference.Ã‚Â Finally, there are many things you can do to reduce stress and anxiety. Some find relaxation techniques like yoga or meditation to be helpful. Others find that spending time in nature or being around loved ones helps them feel more relaxed.Ã‚Â If you\'re feeling like you\'re not able to cope with your stress, it\'s important to seek professional help. There are many effective treatments available for anxiety and depression.'),('Q_028','M3',' Depression and anxiety are two common mental health issues that can be very distressing.Ã‚Â  They are often treated with medication and psychotherapy.Ã‚Â  You will want to talk to your doctor about which treatment option is best for you.Ã‚Â  There are also some things that you can do on your own to help manage your depression and anxiety.\nExercise can be a great way to boost mood and reduce stress, both of which can contribute to anxiety.Ã‚Â  Aim to get at least 30 minutes of moderate-intensity exercise most days of the week.\nEat a healthy diet.Ã‚Â  Eating a healthy diet can help improve your mood and energy levels, and may also help to reduce stress.Ã‚Â  Try to eat plenty of fruits, vegetables, and whole grains.\nGet enough sleep.Ã‚Â  Sleep is essential for overall health and well-being.Ã‚Â  Adults should aim for 7-8 hours of sleep each night.\nSpend time with loved ones.Ã‚Â  Social support is important for mental health.Ã‚Â  Try to spend time with friends and family members who make you feel good.\nDo things you enjoy.Ã‚Â  Make time for activities that you find enjoyable and relaxing. Ã‚Â This could include reading, listening to music, or spending time in nature.\nLearn relaxation techniques.Ã‚Â  There are many different relaxation techniques that can help to reduce stress and anxiety.Ã‚Â  Some popular relaxation techniques include yoga, meditation, and deep breathing exercises.\nTalk to a therapist.Ã‚Â  A therapist can help you to identify the root of your anxiety and depression and develop coping mechanisms.Ã‚Â  Therapy can also help you to learn how to manage your symptoms and improve your overall mental health.\nIf you are feeling suicidal, please reach out for help.Ã‚Â  The National Suicide Prevention Lifeline is available 24/7 at 1-800-273-8255.'),('Q_028','M4','I would recommend that you seek out a therapist who specializes in anxiety and depression. You can also try some of the techniques that they use in therapy to help you cope with your symptoms. This can be a great way to learn new skills and also have someone there to support you through the difficult times. I hope this was helpful and I wish you the best of luck. Robin Landwehr, DBH, LPC, NCC, CASACounseling and Coaching Serviceswww. lifecounselingorlando. com401-A-1631 Orlando, FL 32803\n\n## 100% Confidential\n\n### 100% Confidential\n\nAll of the services that I provide are confidential. I will not share any information that you share with me with anyone else. I also understand that you may have questions about confidentiality. If you have any questions, please feel free to ask. ## 24/7 Access\n\n### 24/7 Access\n\nI am available 24/7 to answer any questions that you may have. I also provide emergency services if you are in need. I also provide emergency'),('Q_028','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are going through a difficult time. I would encourage you to seek out a therapist who can help you work through your anxiety and depression. A therapist can help you identify the root causes of your anxiety and depression and develop coping strategies to manage your symptoms. It\'s impor