tart by telling him you saw the messages in his phone. Ã‚Â If the messages had nothing to do with work, then follow up the first message by asking him what they were about. Ã‚Â Be open to his response because he may have a totally logical explanation that may satisfy you.'),('Q_060','M3',' I believe the best way to approach your boyfriend is to do it in a calm, non-confrontational manner. Instead of asking him if he\'s been texting other women, you could start by saying something like, \"I saw that you texted your coworker quite a bit recently. I know you two work together, but I was wondering what it is you\'re texting about.\" That way, he will feel less defensive and more able to answer your questions without feeling like he\'s being attacked. If he is open to the conversation, you can ask him if he has any friends or coworkers who are women and what it is like for him to have them in his life. This will help you understand more about his relationship with other women and what his intentions are. If he becomes defensive or angry, you may want to talk to him about how he\'s feeling and what you can do to help. It\'s important to make sure that you both feel comfortable talking about this issue and that you\'re both on the same page about the importance of communication in your relationship.'),('Q_060','M4','Hi, I\'m sorry to hear that you are having this problem. I would suggest that you ask him about his phone and if he is willing to give it to you to look through. If he is willing to do that, then you can see what he is texting. If he is not willing to give you his phone, then you can ask him to show you what he is texting. If he is not willing to do either of those, then you can ask him to show you his phone. If he is not willing to do any of that, then you can ask him to show you his phone'),('Q_060','M5','I would ask him directly about it. If he is not willing to tell you, then you may want to consider if you are willing to continue the relationship. If you are, then you may want to ask him why he is not willing to tell you. If he is not willing to tell'),('Q_061','M0','The answer depends entirely on which interest is stronger for you.If the reliable caretaker man is not someone with whom you\'d have fun, lively conversations, understand each other, be sexually compatible, or romantically attracted, and your primary interest is in someone who\' steadily manage the kids, household, and finances, then he is the right one for you!The problem is you may not be happy longterm with someone to whom you feel no romantic compatibility.Â Consider the drawback if you reach the moment of restlessness romantically and are with someone on whom you depend to take care of your kids.Since you have feelings for him, then wait several months longer to see whether or not you can imagine yourself romantically happy with the steady guy.If the other guy who is also the bio dad, isn\'t involved with his own kids, then he seems like a poor choice of someone to be with longterm.'),('Q_061','M2',' You are in a tough position where you are loving two different people.Ã‚Â  I have worked with many clients who have gone through a similar situation.Ã‚Â  You may be trying to make a decision about which man to be with and wondering what is the \"right\" choice.Ã‚Â  There is no right or wrong choice, because both men offer different qualities to your life.Ã‚Â  What is most important is that you have clarity around what you need and that you are being honest with each man.Ã‚Â  It might be helpful for you to explore a little bit further about what you are looking for in a relationship so that you can have a more informed choice.'),('Q_061','M3',' Thank you for sharing with me. It sounds like you have a very complicated situation that may require some outside help. If you haven\'t talked with a counselor about your situation, I would really recommend you do. They can help you explore your feelings and find ways to work through this situation.'),('Q_061','M4