 a counselor or therapist if you need additional support. \nThere is hope for your future. If you have survived this kind of pain before, you will be able to survive it again. You are a strong person who has the ability to overcome this. Believe in yourself, and give yourself time to heal.'),('Q_065','M3',' The loss of a relationship can be very painful.  I would encourage you to find a therapist who can help you through this grief and loss.  I would also encourage you to reach out to friends and family for support during this time.  It is important to remember that you are not alone in your grief and there are people who care about you and want to be there for you.'),('Q_065','M4','I am so sorry to hear about this. I am not sure if you are in a relationship with this person or if you are just friends. If you are just friends, then you can just say goodbye and not worry about it. If you are in a relationship, then this is a very difficult situation. I am not sure if you have been in a relationship with this person for 25 years. If you have, then you have a lot of history with this person. I am not sure if you have been in a relationship with this person before. If you have, then you may have a lot of history with this person. If you have not, then you may have a lot of history with this person. I am not sure if you have been'),('Q_065','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are going through this. It is very difficult to be in a relationship with someone who is not committed to you. I would suggest that you take some time to reflect on what you want in a relationship and what you are willing to tolerate. If you are not willing to tolerate this type of behavior, then it may be time to move on. If you are willing to work on the relationship, then it may be helpful to have an open and honest conversation with your partner about your feelings and expectations. If the relationship cannot be salvaged, then it may be time to end it. I hope that you are able to find happiness and fulfillment in your life.'),('Q_066','M0','If I understand you correctly, this \"maybe-boyfriend\" has done a partial break up, and wants to maintain a partial relationship.Â  Is that ok with you?Â  And, if it is, what does it cost you?Â  He says he\'s \"done\" but still wants the connection.Â  That seems to leave him free to explore other options, but it doesn\'t allow you to do the same.Â Â Break ups are painful, and I know you\'d like to avoid that.Â  I get it that you feel attached to him - you have been in a relationship with him for 4 years, so that makes sense.Â  However, loving him appears to be costing you a lot, without much in return.Â If you wait for him to define what he wants, you could be on hold for a long time.Please don\'t wait another year to advocate for yourself.Â  See a therapist who can help you figure out what you need out of relationships and why you have allowed yourself to be on \"pause\".Â  Â It is possible that once you get clear, you will be able to have a true relationship with him.Â  If not, please don\'t settle for this.Â Â Take good care of yourself.'),('Q_066','M2',' You are in a very painful position.Unfortunately, his actions do not show you that he loves you.It is important that you take time for yourself to heal from this relationship.It is a good idea to seek professional counseling as you navigate the process of separating from this person.'),('Q_066','M3',' The relationship is unclear. Ã‚Â You\'re not sure what he wants. Ã‚Â However, he\'s made it clear he doesn\'t want to be with you. Ã‚Â Unfortunately, when people say they don\'t want to be with you, you have to take them at their word. Ã‚Â The other thing that is important to remember is you can\'t make people want to be with you. Ã‚Â It\'s something that happens naturally or it doesn\'t. Ã‚Â You\'ll be better off if you move on. Ã‚Â Being with someone who doesn\'t want to be with you is self-destructive. Ã‚Â You have to put yourself and your emotional well-being first. Ã‚Â Remember you can\'t change him or his mind. Ã‚Â Best of luck to you.'),('Q_066','M4','I\'m sorry to hear about this. I would suggest that you talk to him about his words and actions. If he is willing to have a conversation, you can ask him if he is still interested in the relationship. If he is, then you can talk about what you need to feel connected with him. If he is not, then you can ask him to leave. It\'s important to have a plan for what you will do if he decides to leave. You can also talk to your therapist about your feelings and what you want to do. I hope this was helpful. Be well. Robin Landwehr, DBH, LPC, NCC, CASACertified, EMDR, Reiki Master, Reiki Master Teacher, Energy Worker, Author, Speaker, and Founder of The Healing Place, LLCwww. thehealingplace. comwww. lifecounselingorlando. lifecounsel'),('Q_066','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are going through this. It sounds like you are in a very difficult situation. It is important to remember that you are not alone and that there are people who can help you. Have you considered talking to a therapist about your situation? A therapist can help you to process your feelings and develop coping strategies to deal with the pain of being in a relationship where your partner is not following through on their promises. Additionally, a therapist can help you to identify your own needs and boundaries in the relationship and work with you to develop a plan for moving forward. Remember, you deserve to be treated with respect and honesty in your relationships. You are not alone, and there is help available. Best of luck to you!'),('Q_067','M0','Hi, Ontario. I live in the other Ontario; in Canada. I\'ll try to help you sort this out. You have a long list of complaints about your boyfriend!Â It sounds like he\'s maybe a bit immature and moody, and these things affect you, for sure. I get it.Â It\'sÂ got me curious, and if I was working with you, I\'d want to know a lot more about how long you\'ve been together andÂ what\'s actually working well between you two. I would also ask a lot of questions about the details of your description. What tells you he\'s \'sneaky\'? Does he lie? How do you know he lies to you? Also, are you wanting to make things better with him, do you just want an ear to vent to, are you looking for validation, or do you hope someone will help you wake up to an unhappy situation? Â It helps me if I know what you want.Whenever I meet someone who has a lot of complaints about their partner or boyfriend, I encourage them first to look at the language they\'re using. Some of your words tell me that you think you know what he\'s thinking (that he wants to fight so he can leave, that he thinks he\'s perfect). It\'s always tricky when we assume what someone\'s thinking, and in an argument or dialogue, these kinds of statements tend to lead to defensiveness and an escalated argument. I\'d encourage you to focus on his actual behaviours and how they affect you, rather than the motives or beliefs you think are behind the behaviours (because you really can\'t know what he\'s thinking unless he tells you). As a general rule, the \"When you do X, I feel Y\" sentence goes far in helping others understand what we feel.So, it\'s fair to say \"when you lie to me, I can\'t trust you\", or \"when you end our date early to hang with your friends I feel like I\'m not important to you\", or \"your mood swings are difficult for me\", or \"I don\'t seem to get apologies from you\". Try to focus on his actual behaviour when you talk to him about this stuff. A relationship counsellor can help you each understand the other better beyond the surface behaviours if you want to improve the relationship.That said, I have to ask...if you haven\'t been with Mr. Not So Great for very long, is it maybe time to rethink the relationship? Unless there is a balance of really loving and positive behaviours that you\'re leaving out, you don\'t seem happy. A good therapist can help you understand why you are stuck in an unhappy relationship, if that is what\'s happening.Â There\'s a lot to sort out here...how to communicate about your needs, how to know when to call it quits if something doesn\'t feel good... I wish you the best as you continue to examine these questions with assistance from friends or professionals.'),('Q_067','M2',' What you have described sounds likeÃ‚Â emotional abuse and unhealthyÃ‚Â partner communication.Ã‚Â It\'s important to remember that you deserve to be with someone who respects and values you.Ã‚Â Consider discussing with your boyfriend how you feel, or meeting with a therapist to talk about what\'s been happening and how you\'re feeling.'),('Q_067','M3',' Hello. It sounds like you\'re going through a rough time. You mentioned a few red flags in your relationship: your boyfriend is sneaky, he puts his friends before you, he fights just to leave, he can\'t admit faults, and he thinks he\'s perfect and does no wrong. These are all signs of an unhealthy relationship. A healthy relationship is one in which both partners feel respected, appreciated, and loved. Unfortunately, it doesn\'t sound like you\'re getting those things from your boyfriend.It may be time to sit down with him and have a talk about your relationship. Let him know how you\'re feeling and what you need from him. If he\'s not willing to listen and make changes, then it may be time to move on. You deserve to be in a relationship that makes you happy, not one that makes you miserable.'),('Q_067','M4','I\'m sorry to hear that you are feeling frustrated and unhappy with your boyfriend. I wonder if you are able to tell him that you feel unhappy with him. Maybe he will be willing to talk about your unhappiness with him. Maybe he will be willing to talk about his unhappiness with you. Maybe he will be willing to talk about both of you. Maybe he will be willing to talk about nothing at all. I don\'t know whether you are able to tell him that you are unhappy with him. Maybe 