g out to a support group for people who have experienced domestic violence. They can provide you with a safe space to share your experiences and connect with others who have gone through similar situations. Remember, you are not alone and there is help available. Take care of yourself and reach out for support when you need it.'),('Q_076','M0','I really admire that you want to express yourself to your parents!Â  It\'s very normal to have fear about how to talk to a parent, let alone two at the same time.Â  Most adults don\'t do what you want to do.Could you come up with what you want to say to them before you are feeling upset?Â  What do you really need them to know?Â  Also, do you want your dad and stepmom to meet certain emotional needs for you?Â  Maybe they would benefit from knowing that you have a hard time expressing yourself when you are upset and can help to come up with ways to help you through that.Â  Â Perhaps you need some space from them when you are crying, or maybe you need to talk to one parent alone vs both at the same time. You don\'t have to wait to be upset to have these conversations either--if you feel you can approach them when things are \"calm\" (whatever that means for your household), it may be easier to communicate.It\'s important to know they may not respond the way you want.Â  It\'s up to you to decide if you feel safe or not to express yourself, but it seems like you want to if you are seeking an answer for this dilemma!'),('Q_076','M2',' Understandably, being in trouble can be very frustrating. Try telling your parents that you like having a moment to take a break after being told you are in trouble. You may not be able to express why you are in trouble at the moment, but if you take some time to calm down, you may be able to express it later on.'),('Q_076','M3',' These conversations sound difficult and emotional. It can be hard to share what you are feeling especially with family members.Sometimes it can be helpful to talk to a profe