elf-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-Confidence, Self-Respect, Self-Belief, Self-Effort, Self-'),('Q_076','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are having difficulty expressing yourself to your parents. It sounds like you are feeling overwhelmed and unsure of how to communicate your feelings. It may be helpful to talk to a therapist who can help you work through these feelings and develop effective communication skills. A therapist can also help you identify the root cause of your difficulty expressing yourself and work through any underlying issues that may be contributing to this problem. I hope you find the help you need.'),('Q_077','M0','Night is hard for a lot of people, so you are definitely not alone here.Â Â Has anything scary ever happened to you at night?Â  Answering that question may give you the \"why\" of where that\'s coming from.Â  If you haven\'t had a bad experience at night, it may just be the time when you have nothing to do, which allows more intense thoughts and feelings to surface.Â Â Here\'s a couple things to try:One thing you could do is sit down a couple hours before you go to bed and journal (if you can).Â  Try to reduce any distractions and just go for it.Â  The purpose of this is to slow down well before you go to bed, expressing some of the anxiety from the day.Â  Also take note of the things you can tackle that day vs what can wait until later.Â  This gives your brain a chance to sort through some of the \"planning\" type of anxiety that commonly comes up when you are trying to sleep.Another thing you can do is make a list of the things you have control over.Â  Anxiety is really good at putting everything you feel out of control of on a giant metaphorical projection screen.Â  Try projecting some of the things you have control over instead.Â  For example--you have total control over breathing patterns, what you choose to wear the next day, what you pay attention to if you go for a walk, etc.Â  You also have control over how you personalize that list to what matters to you.Â  Mindfulness is a great way to focus on how you control your breath, and also how letting go of breathing doesn\'t stop your body from doing what it\'s always doing to keep you alive.Â  Any google search will bring up lots of information on this!Something to remember is that experiencing anxiety is OK.Â  It doesn\'t mean something is necessarily wrong.Â  Anxiety is sometimes just a feeling that comes up without much of a cause.Â  If you can\'t identify that cause, it\'s probably because of a little misinterpretation in the brain.Â  Mindfulness can definitely help with that.'),('Q_077','M2',' It\'s not uncommon to feel scared or unsettled at night. Ã‚Â The dark can bring up fears and anxieties that make it harder to fall asleep or stay asleep. Ã‚Â Having your loved ones close by, and having a night light or other source of light can help bring comfort. Ã‚Â Try to focus on calming thoughts, such as picturing a peaceful setting or repeating a comforting phrase to yourself. Ã‚Â There are also a number of resources available online and at your local library that can help you learn more about managing anxiety and sleep.'),('Q_077','M3',' How long have you been feeling scared?Ã‚Â  Has anything specific happened that you feel could have led to this feeling?Ã‚Â  What do you usually do when you feel scared?Ã‚Â  Are you able to do anything that helps you feel more relaxed?'),('Q_077','M4','I would recommend that you seek out a therapist who specializes in working with trauma. Trauma can have a profound effect on our sleep. I would also recommend that you seek out a therapist who specializes in working with PTSD. PTSD can have a profound effect on our sleep. I would also recommend that you seek out a therapist who specializes in working with dissociation. Dissociation can have a profound effect on our sleep. I would also recommend that you seek out a therapist who specializes in working with grief and loss. Grief and loss can have a profound effect on our sleep. I would also recommend that you seek out a therapist'),('Q_077','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are having trouble sleeping. I\'m not sure what is causing your fear of sleeping alone, but I would recommend talking to a therapist about it. They can help you figure out what is causing your fear and work with you to find ways to cope with it. You can also try some relaxation techniques before bed, such as deep breathing or meditation, to help calm your mind and body. Good luck!'),('Q_078','M0','Social anxiety has skyrocketed since COVID.Â  Plus could be trauma or PTSD.Â  Maybe you are a known person and feel safer not going so much out in public.Â  I understand as a known person in my field depending on where I am it can be a bit much.Â  Or maybe the things you found Joy in before are not as much of an interest.Â  It could be your age or menapause (hormones) and injury.Â  SO many things could be in play depending on the client and their lifestyle.Â  Always best to get a check up.Â  See if there is under lining medical issues and then go from there.'),('Q_078','M2',' Perhaps consider asking that question to a professional therapist or counselor who will be able to understand your situation from all angles and who will assist you in discovering solutions and coping tactics to address these difficult feelings.'),('Q_078','M3',' In order to understand why you feel this way, it is important to identify the triggers for your feelings.Ã‚Â  Once you are able to identify your triggers you are able to make plans to avoid and cope with them.Ã‚Â  It may be helpful to discuss this with a counselor who can help you identify the triggers to your anxiety and learn how to cope with them.'),('Q_078','M4','nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan - nan -'),('Q_078','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are feeling this way. It is possible that you are experiencing some type of anxiety. Anxiety is a normal emotion that everyone experiences from time to time. It is a natural response to stress. However, if you are experiencing anxiety on a regular basis, it may be time to seek help. There are many different types of anxiety disorders, and there are many different types of treatments available. It is important to find a therapist who specializes in anxiety disorders and who you feel comfortable working with. They can help you to identify the root cause of your anxiety and develop a treatment plan that is tailored to your specific needs. I hope that you are able to find the help that you need.'),('Q_079','M0','First off, this is totally expected for someone your age!Â  You are just moving into the phase of life where your \"job\" is to figure out your identity and who you are.Â  It\'s no surprise you are afraid of people, if that\'s the way you feel you are struggling.If you are worried about people harming you, that paints a different picture.Â  Do you struggle to trust your evaluations of others?Â  What makes someone safe (ish) vs. potentially dangerous?Â  Sitting down and coming up with some ways you have done this in the past or qualities of the people you trust now can help to disentangle what means safety and what means danger. We can never truly know how someone will behave, but if we always choose to never trust, then we miss out on connection as well.Â Â Your brain is still growing so the great news is it\'s so flexible to change.Â  It remains flexible for the entire lifespan, but the teen years are really the last time it\'s so moldable.Â Â If there\'s someone in your life you can trust, reaching out for help can make how you are feeling less intense.Â  It\'s never fun to deal with everything by yourself.Â Â Hope this helps!'),('Q_079','M2',' It sounds like you may be struggling with social anxiety. Social anxiety is a fear of being judged or embarrassed in social situations. Symptoms can include feeling nervous, self-conscious, and afraid of talking to new people. It\'s important to remember that social anxiety is a common problem and there are things you can do to learn how to cope with it.Ã‚Â  Ã‚Â  Here are some suggestions for helping to manage social anxiety: Practice Relaxation Techniques. Relaxation techniques, such as deep breathing and yoga, can help to reduce feelings of anxiety.Ã‚Â  Ã‚Â  Practice Positive Self-Talk.Ã‚Â  Ã‚Â Replace negative thoughts with more positive ones. Remind yourself of your strengths and accomplishments.Ã‚Â  Ã‚Â  Gradually Face Your Fears. Start by talking to one person you feel comfortable with. Gradually expose yourself to increasingly more difficult situations.Ã‚Â  Ã‚Â  Seek Professional Help.Ã‚Â  Ã‚Â If you\'re struggling with social anxiety, talk to a therapist who can help you develop coping skills.'),('Q_079','M3',' It\'s okay to feel afraid, especially if it\'s someone you don\'t know. But if you\'re worried about feeling afraid, talking to a therapist might be a good idea. It\'s important to remember that you don\'t have to be afraid of everyone, and it\'s important to be safe and to listen to your gut. If you don\'t feel good about being around someone, it\'s important to listen to your gut and stay away.'),('Q_079','M4','I\'m glad you wrote. I\'m not sure whether you\'re talking about being afraid of people in general or of specific people. If you\'re afraid of specific people, then you\'re probably feeling threatened by something about them which is not obvious. If you\'re afraid of people in general, then you\'re probably feeling overwhelmed by the number of people who are around you. If you\'re feeling overwhelmed, then you\'re probably feeling overwhelmed by the number of people who are around you. If you\'re feeling overwhelmed by the number of people who are around you, then you\'re probably feeling overwhelmed by the number of people who are around you. If you\'re feeling overwhelmed by the number of people who are around you'),('Q_079','M5','I\'m glad you are aware of your fear and want to change it. I would suggest that you start by identifying the thoughts that are causing you to feel afraid. Once you identify the thoughts, you can challenge them and replace them with more positive thoughts. For example, if you are afraid of meeting someone, you might think \"they won\'t like me\" or \"they will judge me\". You can challenge these thoughts by asking yourself if there is any evidence to support them. If there is no evidence, you can replace them with more positive thoughts such as \"they are just like me\" or \"they are probably just as nervous as I am\". It may also be helpful to practice meeting new people in a safe and supportive environment before you try to meet new people in real life. Good luck!'),('Q_080','M0','Wow, congratulations on being in a masters program. You are in a unique place. So few have reached that level. You should give yourself a pat on the back.Confidence is not something that comes naturally. But can and does come with practice.Having gone through two masters programs I can sympathize with your your dilemma.Â So how is the stress affecting you?Is it serious enough to stop you from presenting or is it just \"butterflies\"?There are many ways of dealing with the anxiety and stress. Much depends on how serious the stress is.So here are a few ideas:1. Practice in front of a mirror.Sounds strange but the practice helps.2. Ask some friends to listen to your presentations.Â Not so much for their input as to just get used to presenting.3. Focus on the material you are presenting.Â The subject matter is what you want to get across. Step away from your nerves and get into the facts you want to present. Let the material you present be the focus.Â 4. Remember everyone else is just as nervous as you.Â Share your fears with some of your classmates and gain support from them. Focus on a friendly face during the presentation. Be a support to them in return.5. \"Fake it, till you make it\".Â Yes it sounds blunt.Â But sometimes that\'s what it takes. Even if you feel like it, you won\'t die.So much more can be discussed with a competent counselor. Take the time to let a professional help you work through this.Again you have come a long way to be in a graduate program. Congratulations you have done great work so far. It\'s just one step at a time, take the steps.'),('Q_080','M2',' It sounds like you are experiencing anxiety whenever you have to present in front of a group of people.Ã‚Â  This can be quite common, and there are many things you can do to practice increasing your level of confidence.Ã‚Â  Try some of the suggestions below and see what helps you to feel more confident with your presentations:1. Practice your presentations in front of the mirror.Ã‚Â  This can help you to gain familiarity with your material and to identify your pacing and tone.2. Visualize yourself giving a successful presentation.Ã‚Â  This can help you to build confidence and to reduce anxiety.3. Take some deep breaths before you begin your presentation.Ã‚Â  This can help you to calm nerves and to focus your attention.4. Speak slowly and clearly.Ã‚Â  This can help you feel more confident and to be easily understood by your audience.5. Engage your audience.Ã‚Â  Ask questions and make eye contact with your listeners.6. Don\'t be afraid to make mistakes.Ã‚Â  Everyone makes mistakes!Ã‚Â  The important thing is to keep going and to not let them get to you.7. Practice positive self-talk.Ã‚Â  Tell yourself positive things about yourself and your abilities.8. Seek professional help.Ã‚Â  If you are struggling to overcome your shyness and anxiety on your own, it may be helpful to speak to a therapist.Ã‚Â  A therapist can help you identify the root of your anxiety and provide you with coping mechanisms.'),('Q_080','M3',' Hi there,Ã‚Â What you are experiencing is very common. I am sure that you are not the only one feeling this way. It is completely normal to feel overwhelmed by the prospect of presentations in front of a group of people. The best thing to do is to start off small. First, try practicing your presentation in front of a mirror. This will help you to get used to the sound of your voice and to see yourself speaking. Then, try practicing in front of a small group of friends or family. This will help you to get used to speaking in front of people and to see how your presentation flows. If you are still feeling nervous, consider taking a public speaking class. This will help you to learn techniques for managing your anxiety and to give you more confidence in your abilities.The most important thing is to not give up. No one is born knowing how to give presentations. It is a skill that you can learn and develop. The more you practice, the more confident you will become.'),('Q_080','M4','I would recommend that you practice your presentations in front of a mirror. This will allow you to practice your presentation without feeling judged. You can also practice your presentation in front of a friend or family member. They can give you feedback on your presentation. You can also practice your presentation in front of a group of friends. This will allow you to practice your presentation in a more social setting. You can also practice your presentation in front of a group of strangers. This will allow you to practice your presentation in a more professional setting. You can also practice your presentation in front of a group of people that you know. This will allow you to practice your presentation in a more comfortable setting. You can also practice your presentation in front of a group of people that you don\'t know.'),('Q_080','M5','I\'m glad you are in graduate school and that you are willing to work on your confidence. I would suggest that you start by identifying what is causing you to feel stressed out and less confident. What are your thoughts and feelings about presenting in front of your classmates and professors?  What are your thoughts and feelings about your own abilities to present?  Once you have identified the thoughts and feelings that are causing you to feel stressed out and less confident, you can work on changing those thoughts and feelings. For example, if you are thinking that you are not good at presenting, you can work on changing that thought to a more positive thought such as \"I am a good presenter and I have prepared well for this presentation. \"  You can also work on changing your feelings by practicing relaxation techniques such as deep breathing or visualization. Remember, confidence is something that can be developed with practice and patience. You got this!'),('Q_081','M0','Oh, crying in therapy is very normal! I have a stack of kleenex boxes in my office. Cry away, therapist are very used to it:) First time being in therapy is scary, but you\'ll soon know if you are a good match.'),('Q_081','M2',' Of course it\'s alright to cry! Crying is one of the most therapeutic things that we can do. As therapists, we know that crying will probably happen at some point. We\'re happy to let clients express themselves as they need to.'),('Q_081','M3',' I\'ve never known anyone who regrets crying during therapy. Crying is a signal that you\'re feeling something important and need to talk about it.'),('Q_081','M4','It\'s very common to cry during a therapy session. It\'s a safe place to be vulnerable and express your emotions. I\'ve had clients cry during a session and they\'re always surprised at how much emotion they have in them. It\'s a good thing to be able to express your emotions and to have someone there to support you through that. It\'s not something to worry about. You\'re doing the right thing by going to therapy. Good luck!  Mirella~Image and Likeness Counseling www. ImageandLikeness. comwww. Facebook. com/ImageandLikenessCounselingwww. Twitter. Pinterest. com/ImageandLikenessCounseling/www. Instagram. Flickr. com/photographer/107276172/www. com/photographer/107'),('Q_081','M5','It is normal to feel nervous about counseling. It is a safe space to share your thoughts and feelings. Crying is a natural response to emotions. It is a healthy way to release emotions. It is not embarrassing to cry in counseling. It is a sign that you are being vulnerable and honest with yourself and your counselor. It is important to remember that your counselor is there to support you and help you through your struggles. They are trained to handle difficult emotions and will not judge you for crying. If you are feeling nervous about crying in counseling, try to remind yourself that it is a safe space and that your counselor is there to support you. You can also try to practice some relaxation techniques before your session to help calm your nerves. Remember, it is okay to cry in counseling. It is a natural and healthy response to emotions.'),('Q_082','M0','Given the description you have posted here, it may be time to find someone to work with. Â First and foremost, look into working with someone who specializes in working with individuals with challenges surrounding drinking. This would need to be assessed first since if it has been ongoing, it may be making the situation worse and given the time it has been utilized as a coping mechanism, there is reason to believe that the structure of your brain may have been effected as has been demonstrated by current neurological research. Â There are however, ways to address this. Â As for coping mechanisms, the person you work with should also look at offering you alternatives such as the skills found within the Dialectic Behavior Therapy model (DBT) which has several useful tools to help address the underlying anxiety and difficulty managing emotional regulation. Â Mindfulness, another component of DBT should also prove to be useful in both becoming aware of your state of mind and emotional state to allow you to make different choices which has been supported by a growing body of evidence. Â There are also other tools designed to help repair damaged relationships. Â Well worth looking into.Seeking help is never easy and it is only human to be hesitant given some of the cultural views of working with therapist. Â This is a difficult place to be in and one that is not easy to move out of, but sitting on it is not going to help it go away. Â Think of it this way, if you broke your arm, would you just wrap it up and hope for the best? or seek out a professional to help you set the break and teach you how to mend the wound. Â The same applies here. Â Think of it as first aid for the mind.'),('Q_082','M2',' It\'s clear that you have a lot on your mind, and that your current drinking habit is a way to cope with your anxiety. Perhaps the first step is to address the underlying problem, which seems to be a lack of trust in your wife. This is a very common problem, and talking to a therapist can help you sort out your feelings and make some decisions about what you want to do. Once you have a better understanding of why you\'re drinking, it will be easier to address the addiction.'),('Q_082','M3',' Hello there.Ã‚Â  Thank you for reaching out. Your concerns about your wife and your drinking sound like they\'re really weighing heavily on you. I\'m not surprised that you\'re looking for a way to relieve the stress that you\'re experiencing. Ã‚Â I think it would be a good idea for you to speak with a mental health therapist about these concerns. A therapist who is trained in couples counseling could help you work through these issues with your wife. It sounds like you\'re having some difficulties managing your emotions. A therapist could also help you with addressing those problems. Ã‚Â If you\'d like some information on mental health therapists, please let me know.Ã‚Â  I\'m glad you reached out. It sounds like you\'re struggling, but there are resources available to help you.'),('Q_082','M4','I would recommend that you seek out a therapist who specializes in anxiety and depression. You may benefit from some counseling to help you work through some of these issues. You may also benefit from some medication to help you cope with some of these issues. I would also recommend that you seek out a therapist who specializes in substance abuse. You may benefit from some counseling to help you work through your drinking problem. I hope this was of some benefit to you. Be well. Robin Landwehr, DBH, LPC, NCC, CCSP, CASACertified, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAPT, BAP'),('Q_082','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are feeling insecure in your relationship. It sounds like you are experiencing some anxiety and stress. It is important to address these feelings and find healthy ways to cope with them. Have you considered talking to a therapist about your concerns? They can help you work through your emotions and develop coping strategies. Additionally, it may be helpful to have an open and honest conversation with your wife about your feelings. Communication is key in any relationship. I hope you find the support and guidance you need to feel more secure in your life. Best of luck to you!'),('Q_083','M0','I\'m sorry you\'re going through that.Â  Panic attacks are terrifying.One thing to start with is knowing that panic attacks are not going to hurt you and your anxiety will come down with time.Â  Fighting that process can sometimes heighten symptoms because your brain wants the message of panic to be heard.Â  Some of the best ways to counter that message is through focusing on the present moment through sensations or breathing.Â  Taking deep breaths allows your body and brain to slow down, sending the message that there\'s no present danger.Â  Focusing on the present can also send the same message, as anxiety typically throws us into the \"what ifs\" of the future.Â  If you search google or pinterest, there are tons of methods you can use for this---some people prefer to focus on colors, shapes, smells, textures, etc., while other prefer to pay attention to internal sensations.Â Â There are also apps that can help with these techniques, such as Calm and Headspace.Â  They work best when you aren\'t in a panic attack or when you feel one coming on.Â  If you are already at the peak of an attack, they can still help, it just may take a bit longer.Â Â Some clients I have like to track their anxiety with a scale system.Â  Let\'s say you scale your anxiety at an 8 out of 10, do some breathing exercises for 5 minutes, then scale it again.Â  It\'s likely the anxiety decreased, at least to a 7 or 7.5.Â  Doing this can give you some physical proof that you have some control over your body.Â  You can also scale it without the breathing to see how it just fluctuates on its own.Â  Anxiety will always go down and you can see that happening via numbers.Â  This method will let you see the light at the end of the tunnel.There are other ways that might work for you via a quick google search, or through therapy.Â  Keep trying new things until you find what works best for you!'),('Q_083','M2',' Hi!Ã‚Â Thank you for reaching out to me.Ã‚Â I\'m sorry to hear your anxiety has been so severe for you lately. I am an experienced Licensed Clinical Social Worker in the U.S. and I\'m here to help. How has the panic affected your life?'),('Q_083','M3',' It sounds like you\'re having a tough time. Panic attacks can be really scary and debilitating. Ã‚Â  Anxiety can be a difficult emotion to manage. It can feel overwhelming and can make it difficult to do everyday tasks.Ã‚Â  There are some resources that can help if you\'re feeling overwhelmed. The NHS website has some resources and apps that can help you manage your anxiety and panic attacks. You can also contact your GP or mental health professional for help.'),('Q_083','M4','I would recommend that you seek out a therapist who specializes in anxiety disorders. Anxiety disorders are not easy to treat, but with the right therapist, you can learn ways to cope with your symptoms. I would also recommend that you seek out a therapist who specializes in EMDR therapy. EMDR therapy has been shown to be very effective in treating anxiety disorders. If you are interested in learning more about EMDR therapy, you can visit www. emd. com. I wish you the best of luck in your treatment. Robin Landwehr, DBH, LPC, NCC, CCSP, CASAC, CASP, CAS, CASep, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS, CAS,'),('Q_083','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are experiencing anxiety and panic attacks. I would recommend that you seek out a therapist who specializes in anxiety disorders. They can help you to identify the root cause of your anxiety and develop coping mechanisms to manage it. There are also many self-help books and online resources that can be helpful in managing anxiety. I hope you find the support you need to feel better.'),('Q_084','M0','Overwhelming fear, social anxiety and depression are especially painful because they make behaving constructively a challenge. Â But there are also lots of examples of folks who have successfully worked their way through this. Â So there is hope! Â Â In addition to the suggestion to visit your doctor (who may prescribe a medication to help you relax), there are many social service agencies who provide free counseling or take medicaid. Â A good CBT therapist will help you look at your thinking so that you may see how you are distorting your thoughts. Â Behavior is also important. Â Despite how you may feel: it is helpful to go out, to do things that relax you (maybe a yoga class or a meditation class?). Â Exercise. Diet. Eat well. Think back on the things that you used to do that helped in the past, and force yourself to do these things again. Â I know that this seems hard, but it beats the alternative, doesn\'t it? Â Of course, I recommend you pick up a copy of my book, Living Yes, which will help you look at these and other ideas to help you out. Â I hope you get unstuck soon! Â ~Mark (www.MarkMorrisLCSW.com and www.LivingYes.org)'),('Q_084','M2',' It seems like you have a tough situation on your hands. My suggestion is that you try to find a free therapy service, there are several in the UK. If the therapist you find is not the right fit, keep searching. Therapy is one of the best investments you can make for your own wellbeing. The cost is worth it, it will help you manage your stress and build your self-esteem. Once you are feeling better, you will be more likely to secure a job.Good luck!'),('Q_084','M3',' It appears that you are in a difficult situation with very limited resources. As a result, your needs are not being met. It\'s understandable how living with your bipolar mother in such close quarters would cause a great deal of stress.Ã‚Â Ã‚Â In order to receive therapy, it\'s very important that you contact your local Department of Social Services and see if you qualify for Medicaid. Ã‚Â They can get you set up with an assessment and therapy.Ã‚Â Ã‚Â Additionally, your local Department of Social Services can also provide you with help in finding a job and other social services.Ã‚Â Ã‚Â It would be wise to contact them as soon as possible, as there is a waiting list for therapy.Ã‚Â Ã‚Â I\'m glad that you have decided to seek help, and I wish you the best in the future.'),('Q_084','M4','I\'m sorry to hear about your situation. I would recommend that you seek out a therapist who specializes in working with bipolar disorder. This will help you to learn coping skills and other ways to manage your symptoms. You can also find support groups online or in person to help you connect with others who are going through the same thing. This can be helpful in providing you with a sense of connection and understanding. Best of luck to you!  I hope you find the help you need. I am a therapist in Houston who specializes in working with bipolar disorder. If you are in the Houston area, I would be happy to work with you. You can find more information about me and my services on my website, www. lifecounselingorlando. com. I also have a blog on my website that you may find helpful. Best of luck to you!  Be well. Robin Landwehr, DBH, LPC, NCC, CCSP, CASACertified Counselor, Texas Counseling Association, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Alcohol and Drug Abuse Counselors, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Professionals, Texas Association for Counseling Profession'),('Q_084','M5','I\'m sorry to hear that you are struggling with your mother. It sounds like you are feeling very overwhelmed and stressed out. I would encourage you to reach out to a local mental health clinic or agency to see if they offer any free or low cost therapy services. You can also try reaching out to a local support group for people who are dealing with similar issues. Sometimes just talking to others who understand what you are going through can be very helpful. I hope you are able to find some support and resources that can help you feel better.'),('Q_085','M0','Thanks for reaching out and asking this question.Â Â Social stuff is hard.Â  Even for people that don\'t have diagnosed social anxiety.Â  Some research outlines that our fear of public speaking is greater than our fear of death.Â  That\'s hefty!Â  Shame is often the culprit for social anxiety because we think other people will see the flaws in ourselves that we believe are there.Â  I\'ve had experiences where I thought the person thought something awful of me, just to find out it was exactly the opposite.Â  That\'s how powerful our minds can be!What are other things that people may think of you?Â  Maybe you are very kind and easy to talk to.Â  Maybe you think differently than other people and some people enjoy hearing your perspectives.Â  It\'s even a possibility that they are worrying about the same things as you, even if they seem very confident.Â  Confidence can be easy to fake if it\'s how you cope with fear.To work through some of that, it\'s much better to force yourself out there and have conversations.Â  Avoiding people sends the message to your brain that not only are those situations dangerous (socially), but that you can\'t handle them.Â  The more you avoid, the harder it gets and the more anxiety is created by just the thought of being around people.Â  Take it moment by moment, too.Â  Thinking about all the conversations you are confronted with in a day is overwhelming.Â  Just focus on getting through each conversation, and give yourself credit for doing that---even if you felt awkward, embarrassed, etc.Â  Social skills can be taught at any stage of life, and there\'s always room for mistakes.Â  No one in society communicates perfectly and you don\'t need to put that pressure on yourself.The last thing I\'d say is keep at least 1-3 people in your life that feel really good to talk to--like it\'s not a task.Â  Talking to acquaintances and random people is not to fulfill a need for close connection (unless you end up finding a great friend), but more to feel like you are definitely able to handle conversations without the threat of crippling anxiety.Â  You may even get to a place where you enjoy it (sometimes).Â Â Reach out to people in your life if you need extra support!'),('Q_085','M2',' If you are in the UK, I would recommend that you contact NHS for access to mental health services.Ã‚Â  Social anxiety is not uncommon and working with a therapist can enable you to identify your triggers and develop coping skills for managing your anxiety.Ã‚Â  You do deserve to be happy and to enjoy socializing!'),('Q_085','M3',' I\'m sorry to hear you are struggling with this. I can tell you that this is a common concern and many people are afraid of speaking with others and going out socially. I\'m wondering if you can tell me more about what is happening when you are with others? Are you having a difficult time beginning a conversation? Are you feeling worried that you are going to make a mistake? Are you feeling that you are not interesting? If you can help me understand more about what you are experiencing, I can help you to develop a plan for managing these concerns and becoming more comfortable speaking with others and going out socially.'),('Q_085','M4','I\'m curious if you\'ve ever been to a therapy session?  If you have, I wonder if you\'ve ever discussed this fear with your therapist. If you have, I wonder if you\'ve ever discussed it with your therapist. If you haven\'t, I wonder if you\'re afraid of what your therapist will say. If you\'re afraid of what your therapist will say, I wonder if you\'re afraid of what your therapist will say. If you\'re afraid of what your therapist will say, I wonder if you\'re afraid of'),('Q_085','M5','I\'m glad you are reaching out for help. It sounds like you are experiencing social anxiety. Social anxiety is a type of anxiety disorder that is characterized by an intense fear of social situations. It is common for people to experience social anxiety at some point in their lives. It is also common for social anxiety to go away on its own. However, if your social anxiety is interfering with your daily life, it may be a good idea to seek help from a mental health professional. A mental health professional can help you learn coping skills to manage your social anxiety and improve your social skills. They can also help you identify the root cause of your social anxiety and work with you to address it. I hope this information is helpful to you. Best of luck!'),('Q_086','M0','There is no scientifically established formula for understanding dreams, that I know about, however, many people get a great deal of value from exploring what their dreams mean. It is believed by many that our dreams contain metaphors that represent meaningful patterns in our lives and relationships and if we pay attention to them we can learn important things about ourselves. One thing you might try, to see if you can get more insight into the dream and possibly begin remembering things, is to take note of whatever you do remember, any details about your experience, such as when do you wake up from the dream, how do you feel, both emotionally and physically, what are you thinking about when you wake up, is there any pattern in terms of what happens to you in your waking life around the time you have this dream... If you can keep a journal or a recording device to speak into by your bed, you can try to record whatever you do remember and notice as soon as you wake up. People seem to have more difficulty remembering dreams, the more time they let go by before attempting to record the dream, or if you go back to sleep before recording what you remember.'),('Q_086','M2',' It may be helpful to work with a therapist to work through your anxieties around the dream. The therapist may be able to help you analyze the dream, remember the events, or identify the root cause of your anxiety.'),('Q_086','M3',' This sounds like a very distressing experience that is making you very frustrated and scared. I suggest that you contact a Therapist or Counselor who works with adolescents (a person under the age of 18 years old), and talk over this dream. They can help you work through this experience and find meaning that may be helpful for you. You can find a Therapist or Counselor on line and also ask your School Counselor for recommendations. Talking about the dream you are having and receiving help from a professional who knows how to help you and who has experience working with dreams will be very beneficial for you.'),('Q_086','M4','I\'m not sure if you\'re saying that you\'re having the same dream over and over, or that you\'re having the same dream over and over. If you\'re having the same dream over and over, then you\'re having a dream which is a metaphor for something which is happening in your life. If you\'re having the same dream over and over, then you\'re not learning from the metaphor. Try to understand the meaning of the metaphor. If you do this, then you may have a better chance of understanding the meaning of the dream. Try to understand the meaning of the met'),('Q_086','M5','Dreaming is a natural part of the sleep cycle. It is a way for the brain to process and make sense of the events of the day. Dreams can be confusing and sometimes scary, but they are also a way for us to explore our emotions and thoughts. If you are having trouble remembering your dreams, there are a few things you can try. First, try keeping a dream journal. Write down any details you can remember about your dreams as soon as you wake up. This can help you to remember more of your dreams over time. You can also try setting an intention before you go to bed to remember your dreams. For example, you could say to yourself, \"I will remember my dreams tonight. \"  Finally, try to create a relaxing bedtime routine. This can help you to fall asleep more easily and have more restful sleep overall. Dreams can be mysterious and sometimes scary, but they are also a natural part of the sleep cycle. By understanding more about your dreams, you can learn to appreciate and enjoy them more.'),('Q_087','M0','I\'m going to reframe this and you can decide if this is helpful!What I\'m reading based on what you gave is that you are actually doing your best to manage intense feelings of internal dysregulation.Â  Anger is something that is generally a protective emotion that quickly arises to keep us safe in some way, whether or not the situation is truly a threat.Â  The part of our brain that perceives this is not controllable to us, so we don\'t get to decide what emotion(s) we respond with.It does also sound like you are experiencing some significant anxiety, maybe even underlying the anger?Â  Without knowing the context, it\'s hard to say what would help on an individual level but working through those triggers and what is really influencing them deep down could be beneficial.Â  There\'s many different ways to do that in therapy if you so choose that as your path.If you do decide to see a therapist, most will tell you that the goal is not necessarily to control your anxiety or anger.Â  Sometimes there\'s a strong set of beliefs that, when activated, are catalysts to strong emotions that influence behavior.Â  Trying to control an emotion on its own is usually unsuccessful for people because it leaves out all the other powerful elements at play.Â  Emotions are information and the brain sends that information out because it believes we need it at that time.Â  Therapists can help unravel that with you in whatever way you need, whether that\'s with somatic work, work at the level of belief (or schemas), or otherwise---hitting it at these deeper layers can unpair and/or decrease emotional responses.Â  It all takes work and time, so don\'t get down on yourself if the process is complicated or slower than you expected or hoped for.What we know though is that the brain is very capable of change (even if it\'s painful).Â  Â Hope this gives you a helpful place to start from!'),('Q_087','M2',' When you are able to calm down, what seems to be going through your mind?Ã‚Â Can you pinpoint a certain thought or thoughts that are fueling your frustration and upset?What thoughts would you like to believe instead?What would help you to feel calm and centered?'),('Q_087','M3',' If your emotional regulation is a struggle, it might be helpful to schedule a visit with a therapist, who can teach you some techniques to manage your emotions. Ã‚Â In the meantime, here are a few things you can try:1. Pay attention to the signs that you are starting to become upset.2. If possible, try to remove yourself from the situation if you are able to recognize the signs and they are in your control.3. If you feel yourself becoming increasingly upset and you can\'t remove yourself, try deep breathing exercises, squeezing the palms of your hands into fists and releasing them, or tensing and releasing your fingers and toes.4. Some people find it helpful to create a coping strategy for when they feel themselves becoming upset, such as \"If I feel myself becoming upset, then I will take 5 deep breaths.\"'),('Q_087','M4','I would recommend finding a therapist who specializes in anxiety and anger management. You can also try some of the techniques that they use in therapy to help you calm down. I would also recommend some of the exercises that they do in therapy to help you learn how to control your emotions. I hope this was helpful. Be well. Robin Landwehr, DBH, LPC, NCC, CCSP, CASACertified Counselor, EMDR, Reiki Master, Reiki Master Teacher, Energy Worker, Reiki Practitioner, Reiki