nderstandable. Ã‚Â Long-distance relationships are challenging, and it takes a lot of work to make them work. Ã‚Â I can offer you some suggestions to cope with the distance:1). Ã‚Â Schedule regular video dates. Ã‚Â Use Skype, Zoom, or Facetime to stay connected with your partner. Ã‚Â Schedule regular video dates so that you have something to look forward to, and you have time to connect with your partner in a meaningful way.2). Ã‚Â Stay connected with your partner through phone calls and text messages. Ã‚Â Send your partner text messages throughout the day to let them know that you are thinking of them. Ã‚Â Talk to your partner on the phone at least once a week.3). Ã‚Â Make sure that you are taking care of yourself. Ã‚Â Eat healthy foods, get regular exercise, and get enough sleep. Ã‚Â When you are stressed, it is hard to cope with long-distance relationships. Ã‚Â Make sure that you are taking the time to do the things that you need to do to take care of yourself.4). Ã‚Â Keep in mind that the distance is temporary. Ã‚Â As hard as it is to be apart from your partner, remember that the distance is only temporary. Ã‚Â Your partner will be back before you know it.5). Ã‚Â Seek professional help if you need it. Ã‚Â If you feel like you are struggling with long-distance, consider seeking professional help from a therapist or counselor. Ã‚Â A therapist can help you cope with the challenges of long-distance and develop strategies to make the relationship work.'),('Q_089','M4','I\'m sorry to hear that you are feeling this way. I\'m not sure how long you have been apart, but I can imagine that it\'s been a while. It\'s hard to be apart from someone you love. I\'m not sure if you have any idea of how much time you have left until you see each other again. If you do, maybe you can try to find a way to make it through the time you have. It\'s not easy to be apart from someone you love, but it\'s also not easy to be apart from someone you love. It\'s'),('Q_089','M5','It sounds like you are feeling very lonely and sad. It is normal to feel this way when you are apart from someone you love. It is also normal to feel like it won\'t last. It is important to remember that you are not alone and that you have people who care about you. It may also be helpful to talk to someone about your feelings, such as a trusted friend or family member, a counselor, or a support group. They can offer you support and help you work through your feelings. Remember that time apart can also be a time for growth and self-discovery. You may learn more about yourself and what you want in a relationship. Take care of yourself and know that you are loved. You will get through this. :)'),('Q_090','M0','There\'s a lot of layers there to your situation, and I\'m focusing on two layers that may be contributing to your feelings of discomfort around others.Â  One layer is the daunting news that your son has autism.Â  Many parents can feel overwhelmed and distraught with this diagnosis.Â  The vast array of treatments available is daunting in and of itself at times to wrap one\'s head around.Â  Taking time to reflect or seek out therapy regarding how this diagnosis has impacted you may be helpful.Â  Some parents feel their individual identity gets lost in the diagnosis because they have dropped everything to help their child, and others may experience guilt.Â  If either of these or other feelings come to the forefront for you, it may be worth working through them with a therapist.Â  A support group list is available through www.autismspeaks.org and may help connect you with others raising children with autism.A second layer is the abusive relationship you were involved in.Â  The trauma you experienced in this relationship may have a very meaningful impact on your ability to trust and to be intimate with others.Â  Engaging with a therapist can help facilitate the healing process, as well as paving the way for more comfortable and trusting relationships.'),('Q_090','M2',' I am so sorry to hear about all that you\'ve been through. Ã‚Â As a mom of a child with autism and as a domestic violence survivor myself, I know that when I was able to connect with other moms who were dealing with similar issues, that helped me to feel less alone and more able to connect with people who got what I was going through. Ã‚Â I also started volunteering with organizations that served people in need. Ã‚Â It really helped to build back up my own sense of self-worth to help others. Ã‚Â I started talking about my experience with the people who I met and I realized that I had something to offer the world even though I was dealing with my own challenges. Ã‚Â It also helped me to learn more about the issue of domestic violence. Ã‚Â I got involved in supporting local organizations that provided services to domestic violence victims and their children. Ã‚Â It\'s helped me to make sense of my own experience and has given me a way to give back and prevent others from going through what I went through.'),('Q_090','M3',' I can totally understand why you feel this way!Ã‚Â Your sonÃ‚Â andÃ‚Â your partner have been taking the bulk of your time and energy.Ã‚Â So it\'s not surprising that you feel uncomfortable around other people.Ã‚Â It\'s almost as if you\'ve forgotten what it\'s like to be around other people!As far as feeling more comfortable around people, I suggest you start small.Ã‚Â Reach out to someone you already know.Ã‚Â Maybe start with talking on the phone.Ã‚Â And then once you feel more comfortable on the phone, then meet up with them for a casual chat.Ã‚Â You can also talk to your therapist about your feelings of anxiety.Ã‚Â There are many other ways to feel more comfortable around people.Ã‚Â I believe that is something your therapist can help you with.Ã‚Â I wish you and your family well!'),('Q_090','M4','nan - I\'m glad you wrote. I\'m glad you\'re aware of your own discomfort. I\'m glad you\'re aware of your own reasons to withdraw from social situations. I\'m glad you\'re aware of your own reasons to be nervous around people. I\'m glad you\'re aware of your reasons to feel like a recluse. I\'m glad you\'re aware of your reasons to feel like you\'re in a relationship with an abusive person. I\'m glad you\'re aware of your reasons to feel like you\'re in a'),('Q_090','M5','I\'m sorry to hear about your abusive relationship. It\'s important to take care of yourself and your son. It\'s also important to seek help for the abuse. You can find a local domestic violence shelter by calling the National Domestic Violence Hotline at 1-800-799-7233. You can also find a local therapist who specializes in trauma and abuse. They can help you process your experiences and develop coping skills to feel more comfortable around people. Remember, you are not alone and there is help available. You deserve to feel safe and supported. Best of luck to you!'),('Q_091','M0','Doesn\'t sound like your boyfriend is a source of support and I\'m really sorry to hear that.Â  And my assumption is that the car accident was traumatic for you and still impacts you in some ways.By just reading what you wrote, I\'m not sure what that impact has been on you, but I get the impression that maybe you are now carless and have no reliable method of transportation to get to school or other places you need to go.Â  Maybe you are also scared to be in a vehicle?Â  My first thought after reading this is that I wouldn\'t be thrilled about getting into a car if mine was totaled in an accident.Â  It may even incite terror.Â  None of that is your fault--it\'s an expected response to a horrible situation.My second thought was that you are obviously very committed and reliable if you had a job of nine years.Â  Not to mention brave for stepping out of the comfort of a job to pursue school full-time.Â  That\'s a giant transition that you should get so much credit for, from yourself and from the people closest to you.Â  Failing doesn\'t mean you made the wrong decision. I\'ve failed classes as well when I was just starting out in college.Â  It truly doesn\'t mean anything about you--it just means that things got in the way and you can either try again, or learn something about yourself (or both) and what you want out of an academic career.Â  The feelings around failing may feel raw at the moment, but readdress them in a couple weeks or a month and notice how your perspective may change, as well as the steps you may take despite the situation.Â Â Be careful of how much your boyfriend is contributing to how you feel about yourself, too.Â  I\'m guessing you already felt pretty terrible, then his words or actions rubbed it in.Â  Who do you have in your life that is compassionate toward you?Â  If you aren\'t sure, seeking out a counselor can be really great with all the emotions of a big transition like you are going through.Â  In the meantime, focus on the things you have total control over--your breath, little choices that you make throughout the day, etc.Â  Mindfulness and meditation can be a way for you to get some peace and slow down from the chaos of your life and thoughts.'),('Q_091','M2',' I\'m sorry that so many things have happened at once. Ã‚Â I can understand how this could feel very overwhelming. Ã‚Â I would like to hear more about the context of the situation and some more details to be able to provide a more helpful response.'),('Q_091','M3',' I am here to say that you are not alone. Many people feel the same way you do from time to time. It is a frightening feeling when we feel like we have lost control of our lives and we don\'t know what will happen next. However, there are a few things that you can do to help yourself navigate this difficult time. First, try to focus on the positive aspects of your life. Even though you have had a lot of bad things happen recently, there are still good things in your life. Focus on your strengths and what you are good at and don\'t let the negative things outweigh the positive.'),('Q_091','M4','I am so sorry to hear about your accident and the loss of your job. I am also sorry to hear that your boyfriend is giving you a hard time. I am not sure if you have a good relationship with him. I am not sure if he is being supportive of you.'),('Q_091','M5','I\'m so sorry to hear about your car accident and the loss of your job. It sounds like you are feeling overwhelmed and alone. I would encourage you to reach out to a local support group for people who have experienced a car accident. You may also want to consider talking to a counselor about your feelings of being overwhelmed and alone. A counselor can help you to process your emotions and develop coping skills to help you through this difficult time. Remember, you are not alone, and there is help available to you. Take care of yourself and reach out for support when you need it.'),('Q_092','M0','There is some great advice here that can really help, but you need some direct support.Â  Please find a caregiver support organization, a grief group and an individual therapist to help you during this trying time.Â  Your mom may not know what she is saying, or mean the awful things she says, but that doesn\'t make it hurt less.Â  Please take care of yourself and gt some help!'),('Q_092','M2',' It sounds like you are going through a very difficult time. Caregiving for a loved one with Alzheimer\'s can be very emotionally and physically draining. It is important to remember that your mother\'s behavior is not because of you. Her behavior is a result of her disease. Alzheimer\'s affects a person\'s ability to think clearly and remember things. As the disease progresses, people with Alzheimer\'s may become more agitated, aggressive, and difficult to deal with.It is important to set boundaries for yourself when caring for your mother. Make sure you are getting enough rest, exercise, and social interaction. It is also important to find ways to cope with the stress of caring for your mother. Talking to a therapist, joining 